column1: Which party will control the US Senate after the November 2016 election?
column6: ['US Politics']

I think the FBI emails revelation from October 28th did more damage to down-ticket Democrats than it did to Secretary Clinton. My sense is that voters were already inclined to ticket split this year given how unpopular the Presidential nominees are, and that just reminded them of how much they distrust politicians in general, and Secretary Clinton in particular. Democrats COULD pull it out, but I'm giving Republicans a slight advantage here.

On the morning of 9 November, the Ds will either have won enough seats to have a clean majority in January or there will be a tie at 50, which VP Kaine will break. That, however, is not what the question asks, for at least three reasons: On the morning of 9 November, "after the November 2016 election," no matter the election result, the Rs will still "control the US Senate" for several more weeks; or just enough D Senators or Senators-elect could die (or resign, or be beamed up to the mothership) in November or December that the Rs would still control the Senate in January; or the Louisiana runoff in December could decide the issue.

The D's need to net 4 seats to control the Senate, if they also when the White House, otherwise they need to win 5. Of the 10 D-held Senate seats up for election, only Reid (NV) is currently a toss up, with Bennet (CO) slightly less than a certainty as well. So the D's have a lower bound of -2 seats. Of the 24 R-held seats, 7 are currently toss ups: Rubio (FL), Kirk (IL), IN (Coats), Ayotte (NH), Portman (OH), Toomey (PA), Johnson (WI). McCain (AZ), Blunt (MO), and Burr (NC) are weak favorites, and Murkowski (AK), Isakson (GA), and Grassley (IA) are strong favorites. Therefore, D's have an upper bound of +13[1]

Democrats have roughly 46-47 safe seats. Republicans have about 47-48. Five to seven seats are in play... definitely OH, NH, NV, and PA. Not so sure about FL, WI and IL. OH, NH, PA, FL, IL and WI have Republican incumbents. Incumbents in the Senate win about 80% of the elections, which translates to about five seats. When added to their safe 47-48, that gives them a majority. Even in the Reagan Revolution election of 1980, incumbents won 55% of the time, so that would give Republicans three of the six states in play where they are incumbents if this base rate were used.

It is too far out for polling to be helpful, but looking at 270towin.com, the Democrats may add 2 seats to their 46, with two more GOP and one Dem up for grabs. The best case scenario gives them 50 seats, and relying on a (likely) Clinton win to secure the VP's deciding vote. It is possible, but currently unlikely, that all these elections will go their way.

Hillary may not have coattails--even her supporters tend not to like her very much--but there are more R seats up than D ones, and whichever bozo the Rs nominate is likely to hurt the party. It will be important, by which I mean useful, to track state-by-state polls and predictions this year, since it is going to be quite close, probably.

It's early to make a confident forecast, with the Presidential candidates not yet determined. However, one can attempt a generic prediction along the following lines. 1. 34 Senate seats will be contested, 24 of them Republican. 2. These seats were last contested in 2010, a great year for the Republicans who used the newly introduced "Obamacare" to good effect. 3. 2010 was a mid-term year whereas this time turnout turnout is expected to be higher and this usually helps the Democrats. Also, I don't see any issue as emotive as Obamacare this time,. 4. It looks like the economy will continue to grow, though probably at a slower rate, and though there is a possibility of foreign policy setbacks (Iran, Syria etc) it is more likely there won't be. 5.Contrasted to the Republican candidates, the Democrats appear in much better shape, and Obama's own popularity graph seems to be rising above his earlier lows. 6. If the Republicans lose 5 seats out of their 24, they'll end up with 49 and without a majority. With the conditions listed above helping the Democrats, a loss of 5 seats seems more likely than not. 7. Getting into specifics, how many of the Republican seats are in states that Obama carried in 2012? Florida, Wisconsin, Illinois, New Hampshire, Ohio and Pennsylvania - of course some of the incumbents will be popular enough to overcome the trend, but I think that's enough to sway my initial forecast towards the Democrats. 8. If Trump is the Republican candidate, the swing away from his party may be greater. There are still about eight months left, plenty of time to adjust in either direction.
